🧪 Lab Walkthrough:
1. Environment Setup
Created a Windows Virtual Machine in Microsoft Azure
Configured the VM to act as a honeypot by exposing it to the internet
Deployed Microsoft Sentinel and connected it to a Log Analytics Workspace
Enabled log collection for security monitoring

📌 Goal: Simulate a real-world endpoint and attract external authentication attempts

2. Log Collection and Ingestion
Ingested Windows Security Event logs into Microsoft Sentinel
Verified presence of:
Event ID 4624 (Successful Logins)
Event ID 4625 (Failed Logins)
Confirmed logs were flowing correctly from the VM

📌 Outcome: Established reliable visibility into authentication activity

3. Identifying Failed Login Activity
Filtered logs for Event ID 4625 (failed login attempts)
Observed:
Repeated login attempts from the same IP addresses
High-frequency attempts within short time intervals
Recognized behavior consistent with brute force attacks

📌 Insight: Repeated failures from a single source indicate suspicious activity

 4. Correlating Successful Logins After Failures
Combined analysis of:
Failed logins (4625)
Successful logins (4624)
Identified pattern:
Multiple failed attempts followed by a successful login
Determined this sequence suggests credential compromise

📌 Insight: A success after repeated failures significantly increases threat severity

 5. Detection Rule Creation
Created a KQL-based detection rule in Microsoft Sentinel
Logic included:
Multiple failed login attempts
At least one successful login
Defined time window correlation
Configured rule to automatically trigger alerts

📌 Impact: Automated detection of brute force attack behavior

 6. Security Incident Generation
Detection rule triggered a security incident in Sentinel
Incident included:
Source IP address
Login event details
Related entities and context
Enabled centralized alert tracking

📌 Outcome: Converted raw log data into actionable alerts

7. Investigation and Analysis
Reviewed incident within Microsoft Sentinel
Analyzed:
Timeline of login activity
Sequence of failed and successful attempts
Source of attack traffic
Validated the attack pattern

📌 SOC Perspective: Mirrors real-world incident investigation workflow

 8. Visualizing Attack Activity
Used Sentinel workbook to generate a geographic activity map
Observed:
Login attempts from multiple global regions
Clustering of activity from high-volume sources
Demonstrated widespread automated attack behavior

📌 Insight: Internet-facing systems are constantly targeted at a global scale

✅ Lab Outcome

This project demonstrates the complete SIEM detection and response lifecycle:

Log ingestion and monitoring
Threat detection using KQL
Alert generation and incident creation
Investigation and analysis of suspicious activity
Visualization of attack patterns

This lab reflects real-world SOC analyst responsibilities and highlights the importance of continuous monitoring and automated detection in cybersecurity operations

Skills Demonstrated
